04310nam a22008295i 9783110531879DE-B159720180821111057.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||180821s2018    gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831105318797 a10.1515/97831105318792doi  a(DE-B1597)477324  a(OCoLC)1049628703  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aREL0400302bisacsh 7aREL0400902bisacsh1 aCordoni, Constanza, eauthor.10aSeder Eliyahu :bA Narratological Reading /cConstanza Cordoni. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (315 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudia Judaica ;v10000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations of Ancient Sources -- t1. Introduction -- t2. The Voices of Seder Eliyahu -- t3. A Typology of Narrative Forms of Seder Eliyahu -- t4. Parabolical Passages on the Disciples of the Wise -- t5. Men with Scripture but No Mishnah -- t6. Late-Midrashic Stories of Women -- t7. Conclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndices  aThe book is concerned with a so called ethical midrash, Seder Eliyahu (also known as Tanna debe Eliyahu), a post-talmudic work probably composed in the ninth century. It provides a survey of the research on this late midrash followed by five studies of different aspects related to what is designated as the work's narratology. These include a discussion of the problem of the apparent pseudo-epigraphy of the work and of the multiple voices of the text; a description of the various narrative types which the work, itself as a whole of non-narrative character, makes use of; a detailed treatment of Seder Eliyahu's parables and most characteristic first person narratives (an extremely unusual form of narrative discourse in rabbinic literature); as well as a final chapter dedicated to selected women stories in this late midrash. As it emerges from the survey in chapter 1 such a narratologically informed study of Seder Eliyahu represents a new approach in the research on a work that is clearly the product of a time of transition in Jewish literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Aug 2018) 4aErzählforschung. 4aMidrasch. 4aRabbinic literature. 4aRabbinische Literatur. 4aSeder Eliyahu. 4amidrash. 4anarratology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig. Stud., Jewish Stud.2018 Englishz978311060424508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theology, Relig. Studies, Jewish Studies 2018z9783110603248oZDB-23-DGF0 cEPUBz97831105313050 cprintz978311052942540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110531879423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110531879.jpg  a978-3-11-060424-5  EBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig. Stud., Jewish Stud.2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060425-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishb2018  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aZDB-23-DGFb2018  aZDB-23-DGGb2017